      <body>
         <div type="entry">
                <head>Theodosios</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Theodosios-patr</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/557</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">548</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="406-407"/>
                    <idno type="althead">Romanos the physician</idno>
                    <idno type="subject">http://syriaca.org/person/169</idno>
                    <note type="type">person</note>
                    <note type="abstract">
                        <abbr>Patr.</abbr> (887-896), author, and physician.<note/>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <ab type="infobox">Romanos the physician (d. 896) [<abbr>Syr. Orth.</abbr>]</ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>
                        <abbr>Patr.</abbr> (887–96), author, and physician. A monk from the <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Gabriel-Monastery-of-Mor">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/226">Monastery of Mor Gabriel</placeName>
                        </ref>, Romanos was elected in 887, after a
                        vacancy of four years, following the death of <abbr>Patr.</abbr> Ignatius I (883). As
                        <abbr>patr.</abbr> he took the name Theodosios. No details of his tenure are known,
                        except that a few canons attributed to him are known in the later tradition.
                        In his primary field of expertise, <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Bar-Ebroyo-Grigorios">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/239">Bar ʿEbroyo</persName>
                        </ref>
                        mentions ‘a wonderful medical compendium’ (<hi rend="italic">kunošo tmiho
                            b-osyuto</hi>), which after the author’s election as <abbr>patr.</abbr> circulated as
                        ‘the compendium of <abbr>Patr.</abbr> Theodosios’ (<hi rend="italic">Ecclesiastical
                            History
                        </hi>, <abbr>ed.</abbr> Abbeloos and Lamy, vol.  1, 389–92); this is, however,
                        not preserved. In another work Bar ʿEbroyo reports that Romanos was from
                            <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Tagrit">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/193">Tagrit</placeName>
                        </ref> (see Marsh, 176* and 186).</p>
                    <p>Theodosios’s preserved works include: 1. an explanation of 112 ‘symbolic
                        sayings of wise men’ (<hi rend="italic">melle remzonoyoto d-ḥakime</hi>),
                        many of which are of Pythagorean origin, as the author himself points out
                        (<abbr>ed.</abbr> and <abbr>FT</abbr> by Zotenberg; see also Marsh, 145, n. 2); 2. a commentary on the
                        Book of the Holy Hierotheos (extracts in Marsh and Pinggéra); 3. (in Arabic)
                        a synodical letter to the Coptic <abbr>Patr.</abbr> Michael III; 4. (also in Arabic) a
                        homily for Lent.</p>
                    <p>Theodosios’s lengthy commentary on the Book of the Holy Hierotheos consists
                        of five books. It is preceded by a letter to Eliʿozor (also called Loʿozar),
                        <abbr>bp.</abbr> of Cyrrhus, who had requested the commentary, as well as by a general
                        introduction, while each book has a separate introduction as well.
                        Theodosios seems to accept Hierotheos’s authorship and, as far as can be
                        judged from the published extracts, does not mention the name of <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Stephanos-bar-Sudayli">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/36">Stephen bar Ṣudayli</persName>
                        </ref>. Bar ʿEbroyo, who also wrote a commentary on
                        the same book, knew Theodosios’s commentary and used it in his work.</p>
                </div>
